[This is the 2nd Russian statement on the possible introduction of BTV with cattle imported from Germany; for the previous Russian allegation, see archived post 20111203.3524 as well as Russia's notification to the OIE with details of the lab tests applied (archive no. 20111231.3723). The positive reactions recorded in other species (sheep and goats) of the same outbreak, in addition to cattle, may be interpreted as suggestive that the (allegedly) introduced BTV circulated within the involved premises.

This event deserves further elucidation. Preferably, the Russian samples be investigated also by an OIE BT reference laboratory, to confirm -- or negate -- the suspected international spread and particularly the assumption that a novel serotype is involved.

Germany has presented, during the last meeting of SCFCAH (Standing Committee on the Food Chain and Animal Health) (11-12 Jan 2012) in Brussels, its document "Bluetongue in the Federal Republic of Germany: final report" in which epidemiological data suggestive of this country's freedom from BTV were included, concluding: "Germany requests the free status of bluetongue from xy.01.2012 (to be agreed with BE, NL, LU) and will lift the restriction zone". The presentation is available at http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/presentations/1112012012_bt_germany_en.pdf.

For Russia's history of BTV, please refer to the detailed commentary in ProMED-mail archive no. 20111203.3524. - Mod.AS]

Kaluga region is located in western Russia; it can be located on the maps at http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/commonwealth/russiaaddivisions.jpg and http://healthmap.org/r/1GBd. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
